result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

The defendant Walter S Newago Jr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Walter S Newago Jr is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Walter S Newago Jr was found guilty of Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Obtain an OWI assessment, follow through with all treatment recommendations within the first six months of this agreement or as directed by the Criminal Justice Program Coordinator, Brenda Spurlock.
Submit to any screening and assessment as recommended by the Criminal Justice Program.  Follow through on any and all recommendations of the assessment.

Defendant shall avoid all conduct that is prohibited by criminal statutes of the State of Wisconsin, criminal or traffic statutes of any other state within the United States, or by municipal ordinance in any municipality, which conduct rises to the level of probable cause to believe that he/she has committed any such violation of the law.  The court shall determine this probable cause based on review of written law enforcement reports alone, without any formal charges, citations, or court proceedings being necessary. Defendant will not possess or consume any alcohol or other mind altering substances, including substances marked as synthetic marijuana.  Defendant will not be present at any location where mind altering substances are possessed or consumed, for example any restaurants where alcohol is sold; casinos; taverns or bars.

Provide the Criminal Justice Coordinator, Brenda Spurlock, with current phone number and address in writing.  Notify Criminal Justice Program Coordinator, Brenda Spurlock, in writing, within forty-eight (48) hours of any change of address or phone number.  Report to the Criminal Justice Program Coordinator, Brenda Spurlock, for random and frequent urinalysis and alcohol breath tests as required.  Sign all releases of information to the District Attorney's Office and Criminal Justice Program Coordinator to monitor compliance of this agreement.  Submit to random and unannounced searches of defendant's residence, person or any vehicle owned or operated by the defendant.  The searches may be conducted by the Criminal Justice Program Coordinator, Brenda Spurlock or her designee.  Comply with all conditions of bond on this case.  Any financial payments shall be in addition to any financial obligations the defendant has to the Court.  If the defendant is subject to a payment plan on any pending financial obligations, payments pursuant to this agreement are in addition to current obligations.

supervisions.notes: Fine and court costs totaling $579.00 to be paid in 60 days or arrange a payment plan through the Clerk of Courts office
Defendant is to submit DNA sample.
